<DOC><DOCNO> AP880518-0359 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2104EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-GE-Carbide-Silicones     05-18 0202</FIRST><SECOND>AM-GE-Carbide-Silicones,0211</SECOND><HEAD>GE, Carbide Combine Silicone Operations</HEAD><DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Union Carbide Corp. and General ElectricCo. on Wednesday announced a joint venture to combine theirworldwide silicone businesses.   Philip M. Gross, currently vice president of GE Silicones, willbecome president of the venture, which will be called GE-CarbideSilicone Inc.   The two business currently have combined annual sales of about$750 million, the companies said in a joint statement.   The deal is expected to be completed in the third quarter ofthis year, subject to required government review and final approvalby both companies.   GE is headquartered in Fairfield and Union Carbide is based inDanbury. The new company will be based in Waterford, N.Y., where GEhas major manufacturing and compounding facilities.   Gross said GE's silicone business has been second to industryleader Dow Corning, a joint venture between Dow Chemical andCorning Glass.   ``We'll still be smaller but we feel we will have enough of alarger size to be able to have more resources and more investmentin product development and new market development,'' Gross said.``The silicone business grows by inventing new products and thegreater the size, the more products you can work on.''</TEXT></DOC>